ttorney appeared in the case, and thedefault ruling was issued Wednesday by Superior Court Judge FrancesRothschild for Alejandria Loaiza, 20, according to celebrity divorcelawyer Marvin Mitchelson.   Larkin Arnold, a lawyer at CBS Records who has representedJackson, did not return a telephone call seeking comment.   The woman expects to deliver her baby in November, saidMitchelson, who is representing Ms. Loaiza.   The order was based on the uncontested testimony of Ms. Loaiza, anative of Colombia, who said she had been living with the26-year-old Jackson for about 2{ years.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sammy Davis Jr. says his wife, Altovise, andBarbara Sinatra helped him kick drugs by enlisting the aid of hisRat Pack buddy, Frank Sinatra.   ``Because of her love, I had a second chance,'' he said of hiswife. ``Because of her, I've found my friendships have grown deeperand more substantial.''   Davis, who was diagnosed last week with throat cancer, says hewas driven to drugs by ``a terrible insecurity'' but stopped usingthem after meeting with Sinatra.   ``He was telling me and looking right at me with his steelyblues, man, looking me right in the eye. He said, `Stop it! ... Solong as you're going to do that, I don't want to be around you,'''Davis says in this Sunday's Parade magazine.   ``And I said, `Frank, I'll stop, I promise.' That was nine yearsago.''</TEXT><DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Heavy-metal rocker Lars Ulrich attendedhigh school briefly in Newport Beach and Costa Mesa, but theco-founder of the band Metallica doesn't have fond memories of thearea south of Los Angeles.   ``I don't want to offend anyone who lives in Newport Beach,'' hesaid recently. ``I just found that what's going on there was notwhat I was into. It's a pretty fashionable kind of place ... alittle stuffy.''   Ulrich immigrated to the United States from Denmark with hisparents in hopes of playing professional tennis, but ended uphelping start the heavy metal band. He's back in his old OrangeCounty stomping grounds for three concerts this week.</TEXT><DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bob Edwards, host of National PublicRadio's ``Morning Edition,'' has a simple reason for his choice ofcareer.   ``I can't begin to describe how much fun radio can be,'' he saidWednesday at Centenary College's annual media luncheon.   Edwards, 42, said there's a big difference between the NPRprograms heard by 12 million people today and those broadcast whenhe joined the network 16 years ago.   ``In the early days it was more of a free-form magazine. Therewas much less journalism than there is today,'' he said.   It evolved into news, he said, adding, ``That's what was lackingin radio.''</TEXT></DOC>